As a manufacturer of essential oils, I can tell you that your biggest issues are:
Citrus, don't use steam distillation, cold press or CO2 distillation works best, don't chop up the citrus peels as much as you lose quite a bit of essential oil with the chopping process. Use lemon varieties which have a larger percentage of essential oil. For the home trials, use Ponderosa lemons. The oil glands in those are so numerous and large that the essential will run down your arm just by peeling them.
Oregano, You aren't using enough material. You'll need about 5 pounds to get a small amount of visible oil. One of the reasons why it's pretty expensive. (example it takes 220 bounds of rose petals to make a teaspoon of rose essential oil). Oregano does much better with CO2 distillation more than steam as well, as with most essential oils.

You are loosing a lot of esters (the molecules that cause the smell) by using plastic tubes. Because plastic is a carbon based polymer, the esters seeps through the plastic and you loose a lot of the smell. If you put your nose in it, if it is done correctly, your nose should almost burn so strong is the smell.  The reason that the other distiller did not work great, is again plastic, and also directly boiling the substance breaks the molecules down, while in the other distiller, instead of boiling everything, you just use the steam to break open the cells of the plant material and then gets pulled up. Also, the first test was just too small amount of material.  From my experiments, I used eucalyptus leaves. I used about 10 kg of leaves for about 7-8 ml. Lemon contains a lot more oil that can actually be extracted cold. I would love to help and provide a little guidance if interested.
